Layered plots

New plots elements are added using the plus sign


ggplot(...) +
geom_point() +
geom_smooth() +
scale_y_continuous() +
coord_polar()

Zoom In: Layers

Each geom_XXXX represents a new layer

  • data
  • aesthetic mapping
  • position adjustment
  • statistical transformation
  • geometric object

Zoom In: Layers

That information can be provided in different ways: 


ggplot(aes(x = population, y = stores), data = summary2005) + 
geom_point()   


ggplot() + 
geom_point(aes(x = population, y = stores), data = summary2005)

Bubble chart


# Bubbles represent market_share 
ggplot(data = summary2005) +
geom_point(aes(
        x = population,
        y = stores,
        XXXX = market_share))

Bubble chart


# Bubbles represent market_share
ggplot(data = summary2005) +
geom_point(aes(
        x = population,
        y = stores,
        size = market_share))

Zoom In: The aes() function

INSIDE aes() -> variables from dataset


ggplot(data = summary2005) +
geom_point(aes(
        x = population,
        y = stores,
        size = market_share))

Zoom In: The aes() function

OUTSIDE aes() -> fixed values


ggplot(data = summary2005) +
geom_point(aes(
        x = population,
        y = stores),
        size = 10)

Bar chart - Unordered


ggplot(
  aes(x = state,
      y = population),
  data = summary2005) +
  geom_bar(stat = 'identity')

Bar chart - ordered


ggplot(
  aes(x = reorder(state, population),
      y = population),
  data = summary2005) +
  geom_bar(stat = 'identity')

Bar chart - ordered & flipped

# Update code to flip this bar chart (States will show vertically)
